requirements: The core contributions of the paper have been reproduced.

sub_tasks.requirements: The datasets AQuA-RAT, StrategyQA, and SVAMP have been prepared for evaluation.
The test split of the AQuA-RAT dataset (254 samples) is available for use.
The test split of the StrategyQA dataset (687 samples) is available for use.
The full SVAMP dataset (1000 samples including both the train and test split) is available for use.
All Generators listed in Section 3.1 have been set up with the correct hyperparameters listed
Obtained access to each generator model to perform inference
Inference can be performed on gpt-3.5-turbo (any version)
Inference can be performed on gpt-4o-mini (any version)
All models use top-p=1
All models generate up to 250 max new tokens on SVAMP, 400 on AQuA-RAT, and 450 on StrategyQA
All models use the correct k-shot prompt, depending on the dataset they are being evaluated on
All models use the 4-shot prompt provided in Table 21 of "Chain-of-Thought Prompting Elicits Reasoning in Large Language Models" when evaluated on AQuA-RAT
All models use the 6-shot prompt provided in Table 25 of "Chain-of-Thought Prompting Elicits Reasoning in Large Language Models" when evaluated on StrategyQA
All models use the 8-shot math prompt provided in Table 20 of "Chain-of-Thought Prompting Elicits Reasoning in Large Language Models" when evaluated on SVAMP
All outlier removal methods have been set up correctly as specified in 4.2
The K-nearest neighbour outlier removal method has been set up correctly

The number of neighbours used is set to 5 (the "n_neighbors" argument is set to 6 if using the sklearn implementation of KNeighborsClassifier to return the 5 nearest neighbours, note 5 is the default value of this argument)
The method uses the ball tree algorithm (the "algorithm" argument is set to "ball_tree" if using the sklearn implementation of KNeighborsClassifier)
Euclidean distance is used (the "metric" argument is set to "minkowski" if using the sklearn implementation of KNeighborsClassifier, note "minkowski" is the default value of this argument)
All input points are sorted by average distance to their neighbours, and the 10% of inputs to the KNN method with the largest average distances are filtered out
The isolation forest outlier removal method has been set up correctly
The number of base estimators in the ensemble is set to 200 (the "n_estimators" arg is set to 200 if using the sklearn implementation of IsolationForest")
The threshold is determined as in the original paper (the "contamination" arg is set to "auto" if using the sklearn implementation of IsolationForest")

The number of samples to draw from the training data to train each base estimator is set to min(256, n_samples) (the "max_samples" arg is set to "auto" if using the sklearn implementation of IsolationForest")
The support vector machine outlier removal method has been set up correctly
A linear kernel is used (the "kernel" arg is set to"linear" if using the sklearn implementation of OneClassSVM")

The upper bound on the fraction of training errors and the lower bound of the fraction of support vectors parameter is set to 0.01 (the "nu" arg is set to 0.01 if using the sklearn implementation of OneClassSVM)
All Featurizers listed in Section 3.2 are set up with correct hyperparameters to generate embeddings.
RoBERTa base (125 million parameters version) can be used to generate an embedding vector for an input string
SciBERT (110 million parameters version) can be used to generate an embedding vector for an input string
All methods described in Section 4 have been implemented.
The parsing extraction approach has been implemented to extract answers from a generated response (potentially containing reasoning), following the method used in the self-consistency paper.

For SVAMP, AQuA_RAT and StrategyQA, given a response, the full string answer after the model generates "The answer is" is parsed as the answer, after removing for whitespace, fullstops, and parentheses
When generating answers using the top prob method, only generations where an answer could be extracted should be considered when computing the various metrics in each of the experiments.
When generating answers for AQuA-RAT, only generations where an answer could be extracted should be considered when computing the various metrics in each of the experiments.
Model answer generation using the top prob method is implemented.
Given a question, the model generates a single response using greedy decoding
The parsing extraction approach is applied to extract the models answer from the response
Model answer generation using the self-consistency baseline method is implemented.
Given a question, the model generates k=10 responses by sampling with temperature=0.8
The parsing extraction approach is applied to extract the answer from each of the k responses
The final answer is selected as the modal answer from the k answers extracted from the k responses
All semantic self-consistency methods in Section 4.1 have been implemented.
Model answer generation using the Centroid Proximity Weighting method has been implemented as in Section 4.1.1.
Given a question, the model generates k=10 responses by sampling with temperature=0.8
The parsing extraction approach is applied to extract the answer from each of the k responses
An embedding is created for each of the k responses by passing it through the associated featurizer and getting the embedding at the first ("[CLS]") token
The centroid for the k embeddings is computed using euclidean distance
The normalized distance from each of the k embeddings to the centroid of the k embeddings is computed

Each of the k embeddings has an associated weight inversely proportional to their normalized distance to the centroid of all the embeddings. The weight for embedding i is computed as one divided by the normalized distance from embedding i to the centroid
For each of the groups of embeddings with the same answer, the weights are summed together, and the final answer is selected as the answer that has the highest associated weight
Model answer generation using the Semantic Consensus Weighting method has been implemented as in Section 4.1.2.
Given a question, the model generates k=10 responses by sampling with temperature=0.8
The parsing extraction approach is applied to extract the answer from each of the k responses
An embedding is creating for each of the k responses by passing it through the associated featurizer and getting the embedding at the first ("[CLS]") token
For each embedding, the cosine similarity between it and every other embedding is summed to produce a score for such embedding
For each of the groups of embeddings with the same answer, the scores are summed together, and the final answer is selected as the answer that has the highest associated score
The 3 semantic outlier removal methods in Section 4.2 (KNN, Isolation Forest, SVM) have been implemented.

Model answer generation with the k-Nearest Neighbours outlier removal method has been implemented. Given k generated samples for a question, the k-Nearest Neighbours method is applied to filter out some samples, then standard self-consistency is applied to the remaining samples to compute the final answer

Model answer generation with the Isolation Forest outlier removal method has been implemented. Given k generated samples for a question, the Isolation Forest method is applied to filter out some samples, then standard self-consistency is applied to the remaining samples to compute the final answer

Model answer generation with the SVM outlier removal method has been implemented. Given k generated samples for a question, the SVM method is applied to filter out some samples, then standard self-consistency is applied to the remaining samples to compute the final answer
The experiments and results of Section 5 have been reproduced.
Evaluation code for Section 5.1 and Section 5.2 is correctly implemented.
Code for model answer generation and grading is implemented correctly for the AQuA-RAT benchmark.
All evaluations on the AQuA-RAT benchmark use SciBERT as the featurizer to produce embeddings.
Code for model answer generation and grading is implemented correctly for the SVAMP benchmark.
All evaluations on the SVAMP benchmark use SciBERT as the featurizer to produce embeddings.
Code for model answer generation and grading is implemented correctly for the StrategyQA benchmark.
All evaluations on the StrategyQA benchmark use RoBERTa as the featurizer to produce embeddings.
All the experiments for Section 5.1 and Section 5.2 have been run.
All models have been evaluated on the AQuA-RAT benchmark using top prob sampling.
All models have been evaluated on the AQuA-RAT benchmark using the self-consistency baseline.
All models have been evaluated on the AQuA-RAT benchmark using the CPW method on SciBERT embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the AQuA-RAT benchmark using the SCW method on SciBERT embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the SVAMP benchmark using top prob sampling.
All models have been evaluated on the SVAMP benchmark using the self-consistency baseline.
All models have been evaluated on the SVAMP benchmark using the CPW method on SciBERT embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the SVAMP benchmark using the SCW method on SciBERT embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the StrategyQA benchmark using top prob sampling.
All models have been evaluated on the StrategyQA benchmark using the self-consistency baseline.
All models have been evaluated on the StrategyQA benchmark using the CPW method on RoBERTa embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the StrategyQA benchmark using the SCW method on RoBERTa embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the AQuA-RAT benchmark using the Isolation Forest outlier removal method on SciBERT embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the AQuA-RAT benchmark using the KNN outlier removal method on SciBERT embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the AQuA-RAT benchmark using the One-class SVM outlier removal method on SciBERT embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the SVAMP benchmark using the Isolation Forest outlier removal method on SciBERT embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the SVAMP benchmark using the KNN outlier removal method on SciBERT embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the SVAMP benchmark using the One-class SVM outlier removal method on SciBERT embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the StrategyQA benchmark using the Isolation Forest outlier removal method on RoBERTa embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the StrategyQA benchmark using the KNN outlier removal method on RoBERTa embeddings.
All models have been evaluated on the StrategyQA benchmark using the One-class SVM outlier removal method on RoBERTa embeddings.
Results from Section 5.1 experiments are clearly reported in a way allowing comparison to Table 1 of the paper.
Results from Section 5.2 experiments are clearly reported in a way allowing comparison to Table 2 of the paper.
The reproduced results for Section 5.1 match the conclusions of the paper.
The SC baseline outperforms the top prob sampling baseline in all cases.
Across models and datasets, the SCW method outperforms the SC baseline in almost all cases.
On average across models, CPW outperforms the SC baseline on the AQuA-RAT and SVAMP, but has a negative effect on StrategyQA.
The reproduced results for Section 5.2 match the conclusions of the paper.
The One-class SVM outlier removal method outperforms the SC baseline on StrategyQA most of the time across all models.
gpt-4o-mini generally achieves a very small performance gain over the SC baseline for all removal methods in all 3 dataset settings
GPT-3.5 generally has much higher performance relative to the SC baseline for all removal methods in all 3 dataset settings
